00:07:08.420 --> 00:07:12.730
Who was Harry T. Burleigh and
why are the spirituals important.

00:07:12.730 --> 00:07:14.590
First of all as I'm sure you know,

00:07:14.590 --> 00:07:18.470
Harry T. Burleigh was born
150 years ago in Erie,

00:07:18.470 --> 00:07:22.380
Pennsylvania on December 2, 1866.

00:07:22.380 --> 00:07:25.820
We've just been celebrating
his sesquicentennial.

00:07:25.820 --> 00:07:29.660
He was a third generation free man
whose grandfather had been a slave

00:07:29.660 --> 00:07:31.930
in Summerset County, Maryland.

00:07:31.930 --> 00:07:35.970
And with his grandfather, Hamilton
Waters, begins what we know

00:07:35.970 --> 00:07:37.480
of the story of Harry T. Burleigh.

00:07:37.480 --> 00:07:42.370
It is a quintessential American
story one that can tell us

00:07:42.370 --> 00:07:47.290
and our children more about
who we are and who we can be.

00:07:47.290 --> 00:07:50.700
What was it that prepared
Harry T. Burleigh to move

00:07:50.700 --> 00:07:54.040
with such distinction,
first as a baritone soloist

00:07:54.040 --> 00:07:56.670
in his home town much in demand.

00:07:56.670 --> 00:08:00.430
Then at age 25 to study at the
National Conservatory of Music

00:08:00.430 --> 00:08:05.140
in New York City and as a singer
throughout the eastern seaboard

00:08:05.140 --> 00:08:08.550
and as far west as Minneapolis.

00:08:08.550 --> 00:08:13.850
Then nationally and internationally
as a composer of art songs.

00:08:13.850 --> 00:08:17.620
Songs written for a trained
singer, secular songs,

00:08:17.620 --> 00:08:19.820
usually accompanied by piano.

00:08:19.820 --> 00:08:25.390
As a highly respected music
editor at the New York office

00:08:25.390 --> 00:08:30.060
of the Recording Music Company and
finally as a pioneering arranger

00:08:30.060 --> 00:08:34.260
and singer of and esteemed
lecturer on the spirituals.

00:08:34.260 --> 00:08:37.430
A vast repertoire of music
that has generated many

00:08:37.430 --> 00:08:41.510
of Americas most vibrant
music traditions.

00:08:41.510 --> 00:08:43.690
What was it that equipped Burleigh

00:08:43.690 --> 00:08:48.540
to move far beyond his
African-American community in Erie.

00:08:48.540 --> 00:08:51.730
First of all there was no
question that it was his family

00:08:51.730 --> 00:08:56.230 position:56%
who had nurtured him, who supported
him in moving toward the fulfillment

00:08:56.230 --> 00:08:58.640
of his impossible dreams.

00:08:58.640 --> 00:09:02.210
Who demonstrated a
determined love for education

00:09:02.210 --> 00:09:06.710
and a staunch moral integrity
as well as a love for music.

00:09:06.710 --> 00:09:11.010
They endowed him by inheritance
with rare musical gifts,

00:09:11.010 --> 00:09:13.790
more specifically his
grandfather Hamilton Waters

00:09:13.790 --> 00:09:16.240
who purchased his freedom for $50

00:09:16.240 --> 00:09:20.540
and his mother's freedom
for $5 in 1832.

00:09:20.540 --> 00:09:25.830
His mother, Elizabeth Waters
Burleigh Elmendorf who graduated

00:09:25.830 --> 00:09:29.940
from Avery college in
Pittsburgh in 1855.

00:09:29.940 --> 00:09:35.240
Burleigh credited her with keeping
him focused on his highest goals.

00:09:35.240 --> 00:09:39.000
His Aunt Louisa Waters who paid
for his first piano lessons

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:43.180
and in whom he confided when as
a teenager his suffered taunts

00:09:43.180 --> 00:09:45.880
and bullying from his classmates.

00:09:45.880 --> 00:09:50.700
His father, Henry Thacker
Burleigh, a union Navy veteran

00:09:50.700 --> 00:09:54.770
who in 1871 was the first
African-American to serve

00:09:54.770 --> 00:09:58.150
on a jury in Erie County.

00:09:58.150 --> 00:10:03.780 position:56%
His step-father John Edgar Elmendorf
also a veteran of the Union Navy

00:10:03.780 --> 00:10:07.650
who modeled for him and active
involvement in public life.

00:10:07.650 --> 00:10:11.600
Including directly challenging
the republican establishment

00:10:11.600 --> 00:10:13.880
that betrayed it's
promises to the man

00:10:13.880 --> 00:10:19.350
who had delivered Erie's black
vote in the election of 1888.

00:10:19.350 --> 00:10:22.450
Burleigh's grandfather,
Hamilton Waters was said

00:10:22.450 --> 00:10:25.760
to have an exceptionally melodious
voice and here you see him

00:10:25.760 --> 00:10:29.270
with two year old Harry
and 4 year old Reginald.

00:10:29.270 --> 00:10:31.370
This is about 1869.

00:10:31.370 --> 00:10:36.760 position:56%
He shared with Harry and his brother
Reginald the precious heritage

00:10:36.760 --> 00:10:40.550
of the songs and storied
created by the slaves.

00:10:40.550 --> 00:10:43.770
In later years Burleigh often
referred to his grandfather

00:10:43.770 --> 00:10:47.700
and as his father died when he
was only 6 years old it is likely

00:10:47.700 --> 00:10:49.000
that his grandfather

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:53.570
and his step-father
influenced him more profoundly.

00:10:53.570 --> 00:10:56.580
Much more could be said about
Burleigh's family but let's move

00:10:56.580 --> 00:11:01.240
to the musical soundscape that
shaped Burleigh's early life.

00:11:01.240 --> 00:11:06.090 position:56%
He commented that the first music he
ever heard was the rumble of trains

00:11:06.090 --> 00:11:08.660
and the songs of stevedores.

00:11:08.660 --> 00:11:12.950
It was a short walk from his
home on 3rd street to the docks

00:11:12.950 --> 00:11:15.480
at the north end of state
street and the train tracks

00:11:15.480 --> 00:11:19.020
that ran along the bay front.

00:11:19.020 --> 00:11:23.080
Long before Burleigh worked as a
pantry man on the lake steamers,

00:11:23.080 --> 00:11:26.600
he heard the singing of
dock workers and stevedores,

00:11:26.600 --> 00:11:29.300
many of whom were from the south.

00:11:29.300 --> 00:11:35.360
Did he hear jubilees or spirituals
on the docks as well as well

00:11:35.360 --> 00:11:38.730
as from his grandfather
and his mother?

00:11:38.730 --> 00:11:42.070
Perhaps this is where he first
heard the roust about sound, Oh,

00:11:42.070 --> 00:11:47.570
Rock Me Julie, which he
arranged for publication in 1914.

00:11:47.570 --> 00:11:50.480
Burleigh said I don't recall
when I first started singing,

00:11:50.480 --> 00:11:53.830
it seems I've been
doing so since infancy.

00:11:53.830 --> 00:11:55.680
The whole family was very musical

00:11:55.680 --> 00:11:59.080
and they often had family
concerts in their home.

00:11:59.080 --> 00:12:02.080
The first newspaper accounts
of Burleigh singing were

00:12:02.080 --> 00:12:04.650
as part of a family quartet.

00:12:04.650 --> 00:12:08.600
He described his mother as a
natural singer and credited her

00:12:08.600 --> 00:12:11.040
as his first music teacher.

00:12:11.040 --> 00:12:15.410
He learned spirituals from her
as well as from his grandfather.

00:12:15.410 --> 00:12:19.620
In his mother Burleigh saw a
love for art music combined

00:12:19.620 --> 00:12:23.980
with an appreciation of
black music at a time

00:12:23.980 --> 00:12:26.430
when many educated
African-Americans wanted

00:12:26.430 --> 00:12:30.490
to forget those reminders
of slavery.

00:12:30.490 --> 00:12:34.330
Burleigh's life-long commitment to
church music and to an episcopal

00:12:34.330 --> 00:12:39.160
of mode of worship was nurtured at
the episcopal cathedral of St. Paul

00:12:39.160 --> 00:12:40.710
where he and his family were taken

00:12:40.710 --> 00:12:44.750
in as members just a few
years after the Civil War.

00:12:44.750 --> 00:12:48.600
Burleigh attended St. Paul's on
Sunday mornings with his mother.

00:12:48.600 --> 00:12:51.530
The congregation was
known for its fine singing

00:12:51.530 --> 00:12:55.390
and he was a charter member of
the St. Paul men and boys' choir,

00:12:55.390 --> 00:12:57.860
you see him in the
third row at the right

00:12:57.860 --> 00:13:02.240
and you'll also see two young
soprano's African-Americans,

00:13:02.240 --> 00:13:06.470 position:56%
Charles Fisher and Charles Franklin.

00:13:11.530 --> 00:13:15.020
The congregation was known for
its fine singing, I said that.

00:13:15.020 --> 00:13:18.640
A survey of the hymns, anthems
and liturgical responses chosen

00:13:18.640 --> 00:13:22.670
by the organist and choir director
with whom Burleigh sang shows

00:13:22.670 --> 00:13:25.970
that his years at St. Paul's
introduced him to composers

00:13:25.970 --> 00:13:31.120 position:56%
of church music such as
Palestrina, Tallis, Hydn, Beethoven,

00:13:31.120 --> 00:13:34.550
Voreth, Stainer and many others.

00:13:34.550 --> 00:13:37.140
Given the importance of
Burleigh's role in preserving

00:13:37.140 --> 00:13:40.680
and promoting the spirituals,
it is important to know when

00:13:40.680 --> 00:13:44.510
and where he heard
and sang them in Erie.

00:13:44.510 --> 00:13:49.040
Erie's newspapers seldom recorded
performances of spirituals

00:13:49.040 --> 00:13:50.890
by black citizens,
though this main mean

00:13:50.890 --> 00:13:53.700
that they rarely sang
them publicly rather

00:13:53.700 --> 00:13:56.660
than they didn't sing them at all.

00:13:56.660 --> 00:14:00.940
The St. James A.M.E. church
was established in 1874

00:14:00.940 --> 00:14:03.930
and though Burleigh and his mother
attended St. Paul's the families

00:14:03.930 --> 00:14:07.180
social life centered at St. James.

00:14:07.180 --> 00:14:10.030
The early leaders of the
African, Methodist, Episcopal

00:14:10.030 --> 00:14:14.350 position:56%
or A.M.E. church wanted their
members to demonstrate their ability

00:14:14.350 --> 00:14:17.930
to move into more enlightened
American culture.

00:14:17.930 --> 00:14:21.700 position:56%
And they did not encourage the use
of the songs, the cornfield ditties,

00:14:21.700 --> 00:14:23.310
as Bishop Payne called them.

00:14:23.310 --> 00:14:26.500
Created by their unschooled
ancestors.

00:14:26.500 --> 00:14:29.890
However the folks of St. James
did sing spirituals occasionally

00:14:29.890 --> 00:14:32.670
at fund raising events.

00:14:32.670 --> 00:14:35.590
Burleigh's grandfather
was a lifelong member

00:14:35.590 --> 00:14:39.880
of the Himrod Mission which offered
instruction in reading, writing

00:14:39.880 --> 00:14:43.710
and arithmetic as well
as Bible instruction.

00:14:43.710 --> 00:14:47.120
One place we know Burleigh sang
spirituals was in the choir

00:14:47.120 --> 00:14:50.360
at the Himrod Mission where
he led his blind grandfather

00:14:50.360 --> 00:14:53.570
on Sunday afternoons.

00:14:53.570 --> 00:14:56.270
Burleigh would have heard several
of the groups of Jubilee singers

00:14:56.270 --> 00:14:59.920
that proliferated from
the 1870's on.

00:14:59.920 --> 00:15:03.870
The success in the early 1870's
of the Fisk jubilee singers

00:15:03.870 --> 00:15:08.610 position:56%
in raising money for their Nashville
School inspired many imitators

00:15:08.610 --> 00:15:12.200
who raised money for their
black schools in the south.

00:15:12.200 --> 00:15:15.490
Jubilee performances were announced
in the Erie newspapers along

00:15:15.490 --> 00:15:18.010
with vaudeville, minstrel,
popular theater

00:15:18.010 --> 00:15:21.060
and opera troops coming to town.

00:15:21.060 --> 00:15:24.470
Black performers were not
allowed to stay in local hotels

00:15:24.470 --> 00:15:27.520
so black families provided
hospitality.

00:15:27.520 --> 00:15:31.350
And it was common for travelling
musicians to perform at a reception

00:15:31.350 --> 00:15:34.380
or gathering after the concert.

00:15:34.380 --> 00:15:37.550
Burleigh would have heard
and no doubt met some

00:15:37.550 --> 00:15:38.850
of the finest black singers

00:15:38.850 --> 00:15:43.130
of his time before he
left for New York City.

00:15:43.130 --> 00:15:46.710
When the New Orleans University
jubilee singers came to Erie

00:15:46.710 --> 00:15:50.380
in May 1888 Burleigh
joined the troop.

00:15:50.380 --> 00:15:54.650
Travelling with them until they
returned to Erie in December.

00:15:54.650 --> 00:15:59.110
So Burleigh was familiar with
the diverse repertoire presented

00:15:59.110 --> 00:16:00.930
by the touring jubilee singers.

00:16:00.930 --> 00:16:05.030
Jubilee songs, sacred songs,
secular plantation songs,

00:16:05.030 --> 00:16:09.090
alongside ballads and power songs.

00:16:09.090 --> 00:16:13.850
Burleigh's fine voice was
discovered in elementary school

00:16:13.850 --> 00:16:17.610
and in his late teens while
he was attending high school.

00:16:17.610 --> 00:16:23.610 position:56%
While he was also taking business
courses at Clark's Business College,

00:16:23.610 --> 00:16:27.110
he was increasingly in demand
for solos and ensembles

00:16:27.110 --> 00:16:29.810
at church and community events.

00:16:29.810 --> 00:16:34.720
We know Burleigh as a singer but he
gained proficiency on the guitar,

00:16:34.720 --> 00:16:39.610
the violin, the bass violin
and the timpani as well.

00:16:39.610 --> 00:16:42.050
A survey of the Erie
Morning Dispatch

00:16:42.050 --> 00:16:46.650
and the Cleveland Gazette a
black newspaper founded in 1883,

00:16:46.650 --> 00:16:51.700 position:56%
shows that by the time Burleigh left
Erie in 1892 he was considered one

00:16:51.700 --> 00:16:55.060
of the finest classical
singers in the city.

00:16:55.060 --> 00:16:57.520
In addition to singing in
the men and boys' choir

00:16:57.520 --> 00:17:02.340 position:56%
at St. Paul's he was a paid
soloist at Park Presbyterian church,

00:17:02.340 --> 00:17:06.120
First Presbyterian church
and the Hebrew Synagogue.

00:17:06.120 --> 00:17:10.810 position:56%
By 1890 his solo repertoire had
become quite sophisticated including

00:17:10.810 --> 00:17:14.920
opera arias in addition to German
leader and ballads and art songs

00:17:14.920 --> 00:17:18.480
by European and American composers.

00:17:18.480 --> 00:17:24.530
In September 1891 Burleigh again
left Erie to join a jubilee troop.

00:17:24.530 --> 00:17:28.480
Frederick Louden from
Ravenna, Ohio was now manager

00:17:28.480 --> 00:17:29.990
of the Fisk Jubilee singers.

00:17:29.990 --> 00:17:34.470
Who had just returned from
a six year tour abroad.

00:17:34.470 --> 00:17:36.550
Louden recruited Burleigh
who stopped

00:17:36.550 --> 00:17:38.250
in Cleveland to visit friends.

00:17:38.250 --> 00:17:42.180
But Burleigh's Erie fans
didn't want to let him go.

00:17:42.180 --> 00:17:44.030
The Pastor and congregation

00:17:44.030 --> 00:17:47.700
at the first Presbyterian Church
sent a telegram urging him

00:17:47.700 --> 00:17:51.630
to decline the flattering
offer to join the Fisk tour.

00:17:51.630 --> 00:17:56.620
They made their plea
irresistible by raising his salary.

00:17:56.620 --> 00:18:00.530
Burleigh aborted his trip to
Ravenna and returned to Erie

00:18:00.530 --> 00:18:04.300
but only a few months later
the opportunity to audition

00:18:04.300 --> 00:18:06.110
at the National Conservatory
of Music

00:18:06.110 --> 00:18:09.700
in New York City proved even
more compelling and now offer

00:18:09.700 --> 00:18:13.250
from Erie Presbyterian's
could hold him back.

00:18:13.250 --> 00:18:16.170
The National Conservatory
of Music was founded

00:18:16.170 --> 00:18:20.650
by the indomitable Jeanette Therber
and she needs her own biography.

00:18:20.650 --> 00:18:22.420
Trained at the Paris Conservatory

00:18:22.420 --> 00:18:26.740
where talented French musicians
received the best music education

00:18:26.740 --> 00:18:29.860
regardless of their ability to pay.

00:18:29.860 --> 00:18:32.480
Therber believed young
American musicians deserved the

00:18:32.480 --> 00:18:34.580
same opportunity.

00:18:34.580 --> 00:18:37.560
American singers and composers
should not have to travel

00:18:37.560 --> 00:18:39.920
to Europe to learn their craft.

00:18:39.920 --> 00:18:43.760
They should receive the best
possible music education here

00:18:43.760 --> 00:18:48.870
where they could find their own
distinctively American voices.

00:18:48.870 --> 00:18:52.920
Burleigh was one of 200 applicants
for four tuition scholarships

00:18:52.920 --> 00:18:55.970
for the artists course
at the conservatory.

00:18:55.970 --> 00:18:59.410
Which would prepare them for
professional performing careers

00:18:59.410 --> 00:19:03.350
and he was awarded one
of the four scholarships.

00:19:03.350 --> 00:19:05.150
Burleigh quickly took
his place as one

00:19:05.150 --> 00:19:07.710
of the best students
at the conservatory.

00:19:07.710 --> 00:19:11.330
His music history teacher,
Henry Theophilus Finck,

00:19:11.330 --> 00:19:13.780
music editor of the
New York Evening Post,

00:19:13.780 --> 00:19:16.400
reported that Burleigh
was the best student

00:19:16.400 --> 00:19:18.800
in music history he ever had.

00:19:18.800 --> 00:19:22.770
He had trained as a stenographer
at the Clark Business College

00:19:22.770 --> 00:19:28.370
and he copied his lectures
down verbatim in shorthand.

00:19:28.370 --> 00:19:30.770
Therber had gathered
a stellar faculty

00:19:30.770 --> 00:19:33.810
and Burleigh's accomplishments
as a student paved the way

00:19:33.810 --> 00:19:36.400
for many opportunities
throughout his career.

00:19:36.400 --> 00:19:38.390
For example his counter
point teacher,

00:19:38.390 --> 00:19:41.530
Max Spicher [phonetic] was
instrumental in his being hired

00:19:41.530 --> 00:19:48.580
in 1900 at the wealthy Temple
Emanuel where he sang for 25 years.

00:19:48.580 --> 00:19:51.300
Even faculty members who
didn't actually teach Burleigh,

00:19:51.300 --> 00:19:56.460 position:56%
such as organ teacher Horatio Parker
remined his friends and supporters.

00:19:56.460 --> 00:19:58.950
Burleigh didn't study
cello with Victor Herbert

00:19:58.950 --> 00:20:03.600
but in 1914 Herbert invited him
to be one of the founding members

00:20:03.600 --> 00:20:06.080
of ASCAP, the American Society of
Composers, Authors and Publishers.

00:20:06.080 --> 00:20:11.840 position:56%
But of course the most consequential
connection Burleigh made

00:20:11.840 --> 00:20:16.620
at the conservatory was with
Czech composer Antonin Dvorak.

00:20:16.620 --> 00:20:19.300
Who arrived in late
September to be the director

00:20:19.300 --> 00:20:24.210 position:56%
as Burleigh was beginning his
second semester at the conservatory.

00:20:24.210 --> 00:20:27.180
Two faculty members
published the erroneous report

00:20:27.180 --> 00:20:30.480
that Burleigh studied
composition with Dvorak.

00:20:30.480 --> 00:20:34.870
As Burleigh later explained he
was not advanced enough to be

00:20:34.870 --> 00:20:37.460
in Dvorak's composition class.

00:20:37.460 --> 00:20:41.690
But when Dvorak heard him sing
he invited Burleigh to come

00:20:41.690 --> 00:20:44.200
to the apartment where
he and his family lived

00:20:44.200 --> 00:20:45.760
to sing the plantation songs

00:20:45.760 --> 00:20:49.420
and spirituals he'd learned
from his grandfather.

00:20:49.420 --> 00:20:52.070
Burleigh would sit down
at the Steinway piano,

00:20:52.070 --> 00:20:55.320
loaned by William Steinway
whose store was nearby.

00:20:55.320 --> 00:20:59.370
And accompanying himself would
sing the songs of the slaves.

00:20:59.370 --> 00:21:03.590
The music in which the
composer was keenly interested.

00:21:03.590 --> 00:21:06.300
Dvorak listened intently
and when struck

00:21:06.300 --> 00:21:10.380
by a distinctive note he would jump
up and stop Burleigh to demand is

00:21:10.380 --> 00:21:13.620
that really the way
the slaves sang it?

00:21:13.620 --> 00:21:17.440
But Dvorak was interested not only
in the distinctive characteristics

00:21:17.440 --> 00:21:21.820
of the music, Burleigh said
he asked hundreds of questions

00:21:21.820 --> 00:21:25.600
about the lives of the
slaves that created it.

00:21:25.600 --> 00:21:30.160
He urged Burleigh to give
those melodies to the world

00:21:30.160 --> 00:21:34.020
and this mandate would
eventually become a primary mission

00:21:34.020 --> 00:21:36.410
for Burleigh.

00:21:36.410 --> 00:21:37.960
Burleigh was a music librarian

00:21:37.960 --> 00:21:40.470
of the conservatory
orchestra, directed by Dvorak.

00:21:40.470 --> 00:21:44.400
And he often accompanied
the composer on his jaunts

00:21:44.400 --> 00:21:48.130
through the city and to the
shipyards and the railway yards

00:21:48.130 --> 00:21:51.610
which Dvorak loved to visit.

00:21:51.610 --> 00:21:55.150
Beautiful penmanship was
stressed in his business training

00:21:55.150 --> 00:21:58.010
and Burleigh's superb
manuscript writing made him an

00:21:58.010 --> 00:22:00.290
invaluable assistant.

00:22:00.290 --> 00:22:03.220
He helped to copy the
orchestral parts for the premier

00:22:03.220 --> 00:22:05.210
of the New World Symphony performed

00:22:05.210 --> 00:22:08.670
in manuscript before
it was published.

00:22:08.670 --> 00:22:12.800
And this is an example of his
manuscript writing, this is a song

00:22:12.800 --> 00:22:18.240
that was dedicated to
Sophie Braslau, here she is.

00:22:18.240 --> 00:22:23.060
I found that at the
Boston Public Library.

00:22:24.350 --> 00:22:27.500
Dvorak believed in the
intrinsic value of the music

00:22:27.500 --> 00:22:29.830
of ordinary Czech people.

00:22:29.830 --> 00:22:32.000
He had used traditional
Bohemian songs

00:22:32.000 --> 00:22:34.490
and dances in his compositions.

00:22:34.490 --> 00:22:37.920
Now Dvorak was to fulfill
Jeanette Therber's intention

00:22:37.920 --> 00:22:41.860
that the conservatory would help
American musicians find their

00:22:41.860 --> 00:22:43.860
American voice.

00:22:43.860 --> 00:22:49.580
As John c. Tibbets observed in his
1998 essay the missing title page,

00:22:49.580 --> 00:22:54.350
Dvorak and the American National
Song and this is a long quote.

00:22:54.350 --> 00:22:57.190
Quote, Dvorak's American
adventure was fraught

00:22:57.190 --> 00:23:00.000
with significant and controversy.

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:02.740
The most modest of mean
he was himself a preacher

00:23:02.740 --> 00:23:04.580
of contradictions.

00:23:04.580 --> 00:23:07.560
Born a Czech villager,
a minority figure

00:23:07.560 --> 00:23:10.870
in a German dominated
musical establishment.

00:23:10.870 --> 00:23:15.710 position:56%
Dvorak became a cosmopolitan artist
fettered in all the musical capitals

00:23:15.710 --> 00:23:18.720
of Europe, Russia and America.

00:23:18.720 --> 00:23:20.950
Many of his countrymen accused him

00:23:20.950 --> 00:23:23.660
of turning his back
on his own roots.

00:23:23.660 --> 00:23:27.760
And conversely the German musical
establishment criticized him

00:23:27.760 --> 00:23:32.610
for his inordinate employment
of folk idioms in his music.

00:23:32.610 --> 00:23:37.380
The truth is he lived in both
worlds exploiting the idioms

00:23:37.380 --> 00:23:42.650
of his own culture in a
vocabulary befitting the academic

00:23:42.650 --> 00:23:44.670
or classical style.

00:23:44.670 --> 00:23:48.760
He was precisely the right
person to assume the leadership

00:23:48.760 --> 00:23:52.010
of the national conservatory,
end of quote.

00:23:52.010 --> 00:23:57.320
And we might add the precisely the
right mentor for Harry T. Burleigh.

00:23:57.320 --> 00:24:01.440
Dvorak modeled a way
to live in two worlds.

00:24:01.440 --> 00:24:03.230
How to succeed in the world

00:24:03.230 --> 00:24:07.540
of western European influenced art
music while introducing his own

00:24:07.540 --> 00:24:11.450
African derived music
heritage into that world.

00:24:11.450 --> 00:24:14.400 position:56%
In W.E.B. Du Boas' memorable phrase,

00:24:14.400 --> 00:24:18.150
Burleigh would ever feel
his tunis [phonetic].

00:24:18.150 --> 00:24:20.500
Even though in much of
his career he worked

00:24:20.500 --> 00:24:23.340
within the white music
establishment,

00:24:23.340 --> 00:24:28.890
Burleigh's goal was always to be a
worthy representative of his race.

00:24:28.890 --> 00:24:32.980
Dvorak made music history
in May 1893 just

00:24:32.980 --> 00:24:35.940
after he had finished composing
this New World Symphony.

00:24:35.940 --> 00:24:38.760
By telling an interviewer
that he found in the music

00:24:38.760 --> 00:24:42.340
of African-Americans
quote, all that is needed

00:24:42.340 --> 00:24:45.910
for an American school
of music, end quote.

00:24:45.910 --> 00:24:48.850
As you can imagine Burleigh's
comments were extremely

00:24:48.850 --> 00:24:52.290
controversial, but for Burleigh

00:24:52.290 --> 00:24:55.810 position:56%
and other African-American musicians
his words were electrifying.

00:24:55.810 --> 00:25:01.190
In August 1894 several months
after he had been hired

00:25:01.190 --> 00:25:04.430
as baritone soloist at St.
George's Episcopal church

00:25:04.430 --> 00:25:08.810
on Stuveysant Square where he
sang from more than 50 years.

00:25:08.810 --> 00:25:12.020
Burleigh and Paul Bolin another
African-American student were

00:25:12.020 --> 00:25:15.830
appointed to teach a new
cohort of black students

00:25:15.830 --> 00:25:17.640
who were admitted to
the conservatory.

00:25:17.640 --> 00:25:20.810
Burleigh taught voice and
soul-phage [phonetic].

00:25:20.810 --> 00:25:26.020 position:56%
By this time as the Chicago Observer
reported Burleigh was well-known

00:25:26.020 --> 00:25:30.500
in the best sets read, elite
black communities of New York city

00:25:30.500 --> 00:25:33.520
and Brooklyn as well as
Philadelphia, Washington

00:25:33.520 --> 00:25:36.170
and other eastern cities.

00:25:36.170 --> 00:25:39.350
He was becoming known
not only for his singing

00:25:39.350 --> 00:25:42.340
but also for his compositions.

00:25:42.340 --> 00:25:45.240
Burleigh's first published
composition was a simple Christmas

00:25:45.240 --> 00:25:50.880
song for junior choir published
in 1896 by St. George's.

00:25:50.880 --> 00:25:54.720
In 1898 his first set
of three art songs

00:25:54.720 --> 00:25:58.780
and so began Burleigh's
little known,

00:25:58.780 --> 00:26:03.070
but significant contribution
to American music.

00:26:03.070 --> 00:26:06.000
His first art songs we're
published by G. Shirmer

00:26:06.000 --> 00:26:12.460
but in 1902 William Maxwell became
Burleigh's primary publisher.

00:26:12.460 --> 00:26:18.140
By 1903 when German contralto
Earnestine Schumann Heink made

00:26:18.140 --> 00:26:21.320
Mammy's Lil' Baby part
of her repertoire,

00:26:21.320 --> 00:26:25.580
more singers were singing and
recording Burleigh's songs.

00:26:25.580 --> 00:26:29.920
And I wanted you to see this cover
because Louise Alston Burleigh

00:26:29.920 --> 00:26:32.850
who wrote the lyrics
was Burleigh's wife.

00:26:32.850 --> 00:26:39.300
I'd like you to hear Tenor Richard
Crooks sing Burleigh's 1904 setting

00:26:39.300 --> 00:26:42.510 position:56%
