00:36:00.770 --> 00:36:04.330
When Zabetta Brenska, a
contralto who often performed

00:36:04.330 --> 00:36:07.890
with her husband, tenor
Paul Althouse was asked

00:36:07.890 --> 00:36:11.390
to name her favorite American
song, she found it difficult

00:36:11.390 --> 00:36:15.170
to choose only one, but she said
if I had to narrow my choice

00:36:15.170 --> 00:36:20.600
down to one composer I should
select Harry Burleigh's songs.

00:36:20.600 --> 00:36:25.150 position:56%
Most of Burleigh's more than 100 art
songs did not announce his identity

00:36:25.150 --> 00:36:28.130
as an African-American though
some were setting of verse

00:36:28.130 --> 00:36:30.110
by African-American poets.

00:36:30.110 --> 00:36:34.090
They were songs about love,
beauty, nature, universal themes

00:36:34.090 --> 00:36:38.160
that have occupied poets
and composers for centuries.

00:36:38.160 --> 00:36:43.160 position:56%
But Burleigh's penultimate published
art song is definitely a black

00:36:43.160 --> 00:36:44.670
pride song.

00:36:44.670 --> 00:36:49.650
His setting of the Langston Hughes
poem, Lovely Dark and Lonely one.

00:36:49.650 --> 00:36:53.030
I've given you the
lyrics on your handout.

00:36:53.030 --> 00:36:56.990
Burleigh wrote it with Marianne
Anderson's voice in mind,

00:36:56.990 --> 00:37:00.570
but I don't know that she
ever performed it publicly.

00:37:00.570 --> 00:37:04.300
Anderson's approach to the
racial divide was to bridge it

00:37:04.300 --> 00:37:08.510
through her own very
personal dignity and grace.

00:37:08.510 --> 00:37:10.970
But I believe it is
a fitting combination

00:37:10.970 --> 00:37:13.610
of Burleigh's art song catalogue.

00:37:13.610 --> 00:37:16.710
Along with his setting
of the John Oxenham hymn,

00:37:16.710 --> 00:37:19.610
In Christ there is no East or West,

00:37:19.610 --> 00:37:24.260
based on a spiritual the
angels changed my name.

00:37:24.260 --> 00:37:27.140
Samual Clorage Taylor
had arranged this song

00:37:27.140 --> 00:37:32.290
for his 1905 piano
collection, 24 Negro Melodies.

00:37:32.290 --> 00:37:34.200 position:56%
The hymn, In Christ there is no East

00:37:34.200 --> 00:37:38.090
of West affirms Burleigh's
life-long hope

00:37:38.090 --> 00:37:41.390
that through their art
African-American would help

00:37:41.390 --> 00:37:44.530
to heal America's deepest wounds.

00:37:44.530 --> 00:37:47.640
We need that healing
now more than ever.

00:37:47.640 --> 00:37:50.880
I've given you the lyrics to
both of these songs but what

00:37:50.880 --> 00:37:53.290
of the spiritual arrangements?

00:37:53.290 --> 00:37:57.920
As early as 1901 Burleigh
was recognized as a promoter

00:37:57.920 --> 00:38:03.440
of the intrinsic, artistic worth of
African-American traditional music.

00:38:03.440 --> 00:38:06.880
In his recitals he always
performed at least one set

00:38:06.880 --> 00:38:10.810
of songs reflecting
this music heritage.

00:38:10.810 --> 00:38:15.550
And as early as 1903 his own
arrangements of spirituals.

00:38:15.550 --> 00:38:18.940
This was more than a decade before
he began to publish the solo

00:38:18.940 --> 00:38:21.990
and choral arrangements for
which we now know him today.

00:38:21.990 --> 00:38:25.430
I've given you a copy
of a recital program

00:38:25.430 --> 00:38:29.490
from 1908 that illustrates this.

00:38:29.490 --> 00:38:34.150
In 1901 the Chap Book, everybody's
magazine published three Burleigh's

00:38:34.150 --> 00:38:38.820
settings of plantation verse
written by Maria Howard Weeden.

00:38:38.820 --> 00:38:42.400
She published it under
the name Howard Weeden.

00:38:42.400 --> 00:38:48.600
The editor's note accompanying each
song shows that as early as 1901,

00:38:48.600 --> 00:38:50.970
nine years after he
arrived in New York city,

00:38:50.970 --> 00:38:53.520
Burleigh was championing
the artistic value

00:38:53.520 --> 00:38:55.590
of African-American music.

00:38:55.590 --> 00:38:59.440
This is a quote, Mr. Burleigh
well known as a baritone

00:38:59.440 --> 00:39:04.730
at St. George's church New York and
as a composer has long been working

00:39:04.730 --> 00:39:09.730 position:56%
to show that the true Negro music is
really worthy of serious attention.

00:39:09.730 --> 00:39:12.660
And is by no means
adequately represented

00:39:12.660 --> 00:39:14.840
by the cheap Koontz
[phonetic] songs that have

00:39:14.840 --> 00:39:18.710
so much vogue, end of quote.

00:39:18.710 --> 00:39:24.050
From 1900 to 1915 Burleigh often
accompanied Booker T. Washington

00:39:24.050 --> 00:39:26.710
on his tours through New
England raising money

00:39:26.710 --> 00:39:29.030
for Tuskegee Institute.

00:39:29.030 --> 00:39:32.770
Burleigh's singing opened the
purse strings of wealthy donors.

00:39:32.770 --> 00:39:34.760
It was in these appearances

00:39:34.760 --> 00:39:38.100
that Burleigh developed his
arrangements of spirituals.

00:39:38.100 --> 00:39:40.670
Wouldn't it be wonderful
to have video recordings

00:39:40.670 --> 00:39:42.950 position:56%
of these improvisatory performances.

00:39:42.950 --> 00:39:47.600 position:56%
So we could study the development of
his style of arranging spirituals.

00:39:47.600 --> 00:39:51.310
Burleigh's reputation of one
of the best American composers

00:39:51.310 --> 00:39:54.770
of art songs prepared for
the immediate reception

00:39:54.770 --> 00:39:57.240
of the spiritual arrangements
that were published

00:39:57.240 --> 00:40:01.980
in the 1916, 1917 concert season.

00:40:01.980 --> 00:40:05.470
Many of the performers who were
singing his art songs now greeted

00:40:05.470 --> 00:40:08.640
his spiritual arrangements
with delight.

00:40:08.640 --> 00:40:10.950 position:56%
Two singes played a significant role

00:40:10.950 --> 00:40:15.080
in bringing Burleigh's spiritual
arrangements to the floor.

00:40:15.080 --> 00:40:19.030
The contralto soloist at
Temple Emanuel was Mary Jordan,

00:40:19.030 --> 00:40:23.010
a renowned recitalist and opera
singer who performed a number

00:40:23.010 --> 00:40:27.180
of Burleigh's art songs several
of which he dedicated to her.

00:40:27.180 --> 00:40:29.900
Burleigh dedicated his
arrangement of Deep River to Jordan

00:40:29.900 --> 00:40:33.020
and she sang and recorded it.

00:40:33.020 --> 00:40:37.650
Baritone Oscar Seagle, the son of
a minster in Tennessee who had gone

00:40:37.650 --> 00:40:39.690
to the camp meetings
with his father,

00:40:39.690 --> 00:40:42.310
had searched for appropriate
arrangements

00:40:42.310 --> 00:40:44.960 position:56%
of the songs he had learned to love.

00:40:44.960 --> 00:40:47.880
When he found Burleigh's
arrangements he immediately made

00:40:47.880 --> 00:40:51.490
them an important part
of his repertoire.

00:40:51.490 --> 00:40:56.680
In May 1917 Seagle ended a
recital in Brooklyn with a group

00:40:56.680 --> 00:40:58.890
of Burleigh's spiritual
arrangements.

00:40:58.890 --> 00:41:02.720
Burleigh said he sang like
a black preacher preaches.

00:41:02.720 --> 00:41:06.630
And other singers followed Seagle's
example by ending their programs

00:41:06.630 --> 00:41:09.230
with a group of spirituals.

00:41:09.230 --> 00:41:12.010
Now Burleigh's solo
appearances shifted

00:41:12.010 --> 00:41:15.350
to lecture recitals
on the spirituals.

00:41:15.350 --> 00:41:18.870
And in the late 1920's
as radio waves began

00:41:18.870 --> 00:41:23.300
to cover the country Burleigh's
voice was heard from the east

00:41:23.300 --> 00:41:26.690
to the Midwest and as
far south as Texas.

00:41:26.690 --> 00:41:30.860
Singing spirituals and speaking
about their history and importance

00:41:30.860 --> 00:41:35.870
to American history, we need
a doctoral dissertation to see

00:41:35.870 --> 00:41:40.650
when recordings first started to
be made of those radio programs.

00:41:40.650 --> 00:41:44.620 position:56%
Let's listen to a high school choir,
the Central Islip concert choir

00:41:44.620 --> 00:41:47.830
from New York State, singing
Burleigh's choral arrangement

00:41:47.830 --> 00:41:50.510
from arrangement of,
My Lord What a Morning.

00:41:50.510 --> 00:41:57.510
[ Background noise ]

00:41:57.510 --> 00:45:34.040
[ Music ]

00:45:34.040 --> 00:45:39.040
You notice that is not --
there is no accompaniment.

00:45:39.040 --> 00:45:42.000
Burleigh's choral arrangements were
mostly meant to be sung acapella

00:45:42.000 --> 00:45:47.760
and they're not easy, so this
is a really wonderful choir.

00:45:47.760 --> 00:45:50.800
The St. George's annual vesper
service of Negro spirituals

00:45:50.800 --> 00:45:54.650
which began in 1924
drew overflow crowds,

00:45:54.650 --> 00:45:56.930 position:56%
sometimes the police needed to help.

00:45:56.930 --> 00:45:59.220
The newspaper announced
them ahead of time

00:45:59.220 --> 00:46:02.480
and carried extensive
reviews afterward.

00:46:02.480 --> 00:46:04.920
This is the program
for the first of them,

00:46:04.920 --> 00:46:07.790
it was Burleigh's 30th
anniversary at St. George's

00:46:07.790 --> 00:46:16.190 position:56%
and they featured Burleigh as he
appeared in 1894 and his 1924 photo.

00:46:16.190 --> 00:46:20.470
The programs always featured choral
and solo arrangements by Burleigh

00:46:20.470 --> 00:46:23.540
and came to include other
arrangements by other composers

00:46:23.540 --> 00:46:26.830
such as Hall Johnson,
Nathanial Dett, Eva Jesse,

00:46:26.830 --> 00:46:29.300
John Work and Florence Price.

00:46:29.300 --> 00:46:33.110
These annual service
continued until 1955,

00:46:33.110 --> 00:46:37.430
six years after Burleigh
died in 1949.

00:46:37.430 --> 00:46:42.200
It is impossible to overestimate
the importance of the emergence

00:46:42.200 --> 00:46:46.610
of Burleigh's art song spiritual
arrangements 100 years ago.

00:46:46.610 --> 00:46:49.440
Other composers black and
white immediately followed

00:46:49.440 --> 00:46:55.020
with their own arrangements and by
1925 James Weldon Johnson commented

00:46:55.020 --> 00:46:58.170
that the spirituals had a vogue.

00:46:58.170 --> 00:47:01.440
At first Burleigh's arrangements
were used more extensively by white

00:47:01.440 --> 00:47:05.380
than by black singers but
the enthusiastic reception

00:47:05.380 --> 00:47:08.800
of his arrangements was noted
within the black community.

00:47:08.800 --> 00:47:12.510
The 1917 Spingarn Award
acknowledged his contribution

00:47:12.510 --> 00:47:14.920
in bringing the spirituals
to the attention

00:47:14.920 --> 00:47:19.320
of the distinguished audiences
nationwide and in Europe.

00:47:19.320 --> 00:47:23.760
The honorary master of arts degree
from Atlanta University in 1918

00:47:23.760 --> 00:47:27.140
and the honorary Doctor
of Music degree

00:47:27.140 --> 00:47:29.720
from Howard University in 1920.

00:47:29.720 --> 00:47:35.720 position:56%
Also recognized his role in helping
African-Americans reclaim spirituals

00:47:35.720 --> 00:47:39.930
as an artistic heritage, rescuing
them from their association

00:47:39.930 --> 00:47:42.040
with minstrelsy and vaudeville.

00:47:42.040 --> 00:47:45.690
And making them accessible
to singers, and music lovers

00:47:45.690 --> 00:47:47.140
of every cultural background.

00:47:47.140 --> 00:47:48.440
And that was very important
to Burleigh.

00:47:48.440 --> 00:47:54.800
In his prefaces to the two books of
American Negro spirituals published

00:47:54.800 --> 00:48:00.670
in 1925 and 1926, James Walden
Johnson went so far as to say

00:48:00.670 --> 00:48:04.190
that Burleigh's work had
been the principle factor

00:48:04.190 --> 00:48:05.850
in reclaiming the spiritual

00:48:05.850 --> 00:48:09.780
as a universally valuable
artistic expression.

00:48:09.780 --> 00:48:13.570
This process had helped
African-American artists develop a

00:48:13.570 --> 00:48:15.600
black esthetic.

00:48:15.600 --> 00:48:20.850
The emergence of these artists
and I quote, zealous to be racial

00:48:20.850 --> 00:48:24.010
or to put it better, to
be true to themselves,

00:48:24.010 --> 00:48:28.600
to look for their artistic material
within rather than with out.

00:48:28.600 --> 00:48:32.240
Got its first impulse
from the new evaluation

00:48:32.240 --> 00:48:36.070
of the spiritual reached
by the Negro himself.

00:48:36.070 --> 00:48:40.430
Almost suddenly the
realization broke upon the Negro

00:48:40.430 --> 00:48:45.140
that in the spirituals the race had
produced one of the finest examples

00:48:45.140 --> 00:48:47.930
of folk art in the world.

00:48:47.930 --> 00:48:53.330
The result was a leaping pride,
coupled with the consciousness

00:48:53.330 --> 00:48:58.150
of innate racial talents and powers
that gave rise to a new school

00:48:58.150 --> 00:49:01.300
of Negro artists, end of quote.

00:49:01.300 --> 00:49:04.170
The new vogue that the
spirituals enjoyed crowned

00:49:04.170 --> 00:49:07.790
in Johnson's words a long
and steady development

00:49:07.790 --> 00:49:10.600
in the recognition of their worth.

00:49:10.600 --> 00:49:14.860
This swelling interest and pride in
the spirituals released new levels

00:49:14.860 --> 00:49:18.900
of creativity among black
artists in the movement now known

00:49:18.900 --> 00:49:20.250
as the Harlem Renaissance.

00:49:20.250 --> 00:49:22.590
Or as some of its leaders
preferred to call it.

00:49:22.590 --> 00:49:26.910
The New Negro Renaissance, that
extended far beyond Harlem.

00:49:26.910 --> 00:49:30.350
At the end of his life
Burleigh expressed regret

00:49:30.350 --> 00:49:33.790
that his many art songs
had fallen out of use.

00:49:33.790 --> 00:49:37.520
But he took satisfaction in
the continuing popularity

00:49:37.520 --> 00:49:39.810
of his spiritual arrangements.

00:49:39.810 --> 00:49:44.230
He had helped to ensure that what
he called this great free fountain

00:49:44.230 --> 00:49:47.970
of pure melody would
continue to flow.

00:49:47.970 --> 00:49:51.790
That the spirituals with their
message of hope for freedom

00:49:51.790 --> 00:49:55.820
and human family hood
would continue to be sung.

00:49:55.820 --> 00:49:59.230
His work had helped in
the image he often used

00:49:59.230 --> 00:50:03.250
to unlock the musical
treasure of the spiritual.

00:50:03.250 --> 00:50:07.680
He had helped to coin that
treasure in universal currency.

00:50:07.680 --> 00:50:10.540
He had as Antonin Dvorak
urged helped

00:50:10.540 --> 00:50:13.510
to give those melodies
to the world, thank you.

